 @G[c3 stills_73.png]@L  
		@H Historical Background @L
		Lindum was initially established as a fortress for Roman legionaries. Later, around 86 AD, it converted to a Colonia settled by the many retired soldiers and their families. The era for this mission is circa 122 AD during the reign of Emperor Hadrian. @L@L
		While the Roman Empire certainly saw a decline in celebration of merit, it had other benefits. Imperial authority meant centralization of power and for ancient and medieval societies later, it meant that things could be done quickly without political maneuvering. @L@L
		Some emperors were also highly educated, skilled, and had the genuine good of their people at heart. This was not a given, however, as a bad emperor could cause immense damage, and this happened more and more often during the times of the Late Empire. @L@L
		One notable example of misunderstood behavior is Emperor Caligula, who allegedly appointed a horse as consul. @L@L
		If this is based on reality, for which there is no real proof, it was likely an action to show to everyone how the position of consul no longer held any power and no longer matters. Julius Caesar behaved similarly by appointing new consuls from senators who did not have the merit for such a position. @L@L
		Even when Caesar did not hold a consular office after the civil war, he sat on a decorated chair/throne during senate meetings and, as mentioned previously, openly wore a purple toga which was normally granted only to triumphators on their day of triumph. Purple was commonly associated with the old Etruscan monarchy and thus was considered offensive to wear by a politician. @L@L
		To avoid concerns of the public, Caesar made a gesture where during Saturnalia festival in Rome, Marcus Antonius, dressed as one of the priests of Saturn, would offer him a crown which he refused in front of a large crowd of people. @L@L
		
		@G[c3 instructions icon.png]
		@H Instructions @L
		Governor, you are to travel to Colonia Domitiana Lindensium and, in my name, massively improve its fortifications to safeguard Roman Britain for all time. Rome must separate the barbaric lands of Caledonia from the civilized remainder of the island or else my subjects in Britannia will never truly know peace. @L@L
		It is imperative that you dedicate a significant labor force towards extracting the resources required for construction of walls and outposts, as I have tasked you and the colony at Lindum to be the primary source for all building materials for my project. @L@L
		Lindum is a city with great potential in trade and local production. However, its position as one of the northernmost cities of the Empire means it will be a frequent target for Pictish military aggression. @L@L
		These people are fierce warriors and have observed Roman military tactics, so they know what to expect from our legions. My generals report that the Picts have adopted tactics such as enveloping their targets by approaching from multiple directions, thus overwhelming and demoralizing their foes. You should maintain substantial forces at Lindum, as barbarian attacks may increase in both size and frequency. @L@L
		For its main staple of trade, Lindum is an excellent source of clay and there is high demand for pottery, both in Roman Britain and further afield. Build industry and utilize the Roman trade network to make Lindum into a dominant city in the regional market. Be aware that fertile land is at a premium in Lindum, and that the local terrain offers varied positions for either defenses or industrial/residential zones. @L@L
		A wise governor such as yourself can use the terrain to their advantage, evaluating where settlements can be sited with or without walls, and using fortifications to route enemy attacks into a single area. @L@L
		Do not disappoint me, governor. The wall must stand, and you bear the responsibility for its materials. Fail to meet my expectations and you will find yourself swiftly replaced. Britannia must be secured against the barbarian threat from the north. @L@L
		
		@H Edicts @L@
		Hadrian's @Wall - Caesar will frequently request large amounts of building materials to fund construction of the wall. Special messages will show up as the construction progresses as to the requested materials. If the wall is completed, it will reduce the number of incoming attacks but will require a constant supply of weapons as upkeep. @L@L
		@Roman @Britain - Many hostile natives inhabit the map. Attacks will eventually reach very large scale. The prices on most goods are lowered but they can be traded in bulk. This was the final map of the original military campaign branch so expect a significant challenge. @L@L
		@Decisions - You will be presented with 2 options on how to approach the map: one more economically focused with less attacks, or one with less restrictions but with more attacks. If you choose the path of increased military activity, you will be tasked with building and evolving houses in the "stone circles" present on the map, so plan your starting block's location accordingly. @L@L
		@H Additional Information @L
		There are 8 invasion points; these are only on exposed edges of the map though, never on entry and exit points directly. It's still possible to use pathing and chokepoints to great benefit. @L@L
		As is customary, even though from a historical perspective you should start with a pre-built city on this map, few players would like that so it will be up to you to build everything from scratch. @L@L
		@H Persistent Events @L Grand Temple to Mercury unlocks plaza. Subsidies, lasting until 10 prosperity rating, give 100 dn. per month. Workshops only unlock after the subsidy expires. @L@L
		Due to game limitations, starting prices for goods will be adjusted after 1 in-game month has passed. @L@L@L@L

