		@H Historical Background @L
		The length of the wall was 80 Roman miles, equivalent to 73 modern miles or 117 kilometers (1 Roman mile is equivalent to 1,620 yards or 1,480 m). @L@L
		This traversed the entire width of the island, from Wallsend on the River Tyne in the east to Bowness-on-Solway in the west. @L@L
		Not long after construction began, the wall's width was reduced from the originally planned 10 feet (3.0 m) to about 8 feet (2.4 m) or even less, depending on the terrain. @L@L
		Some sections were originally constructed of turf and timber, and eventually replaced by stone years or decades later. @L@L
		Bede, a monk and historian who died in 735 AD, wrote that the wall stood 12 feet (3.7 m) high, with evidence suggesting it could have been a few feet higher at its formation. Along the length of the wall there was a watchtower turret every third of a mile, also providing shelter and living accommodations for Roman troops. @L@L@L@L

